snippet.textDisplay:
Duck tales explained this 2 decades ago. He may be fast according to an outside observer, but from Sonic's perspective, he's only moving as fast as it takes to process the world around him.

We know Sonic is on auto pilot when he runs to the ocean because he comes back covered in water and ocean fauna. This means he want about to tell he was about to hit the ocean until he was all into the ocean. That's a big blue wall that takes up the entirety of the horizon and is visible from miles away, especially if you're coming over the mountains. Compare that to a relatively tiny landmark such as a bridge, or the infinitely tinier and much more ubiquitous landmark, roadsigns.

Reading every road sign in America, and committing them to memory such that you don't go down the same road twice would be a very unique form of purgatory, but nonetheless eternal. Given his childlike persona, demonstrable impatience, and lovable dumbness, I'm betting Sonic goes insane long before he's covered even a small percentage of those roads.

snippet.textDisplay: Debating a cartoon hedgehog ... but ok; Sonic is not a computer, he couldn't memorize the route and doesn't have a gps, he would have no way to systematically run every street on Earth.  When he ran West he just ran straight to the ocean and ran back, in a short burst of speed.  Sonic is much faster running a straight line, and slower on turns, so a search pattern would cause issues.  You would also need to factor in his ability to avoid obstacles ... my prime argument there is based on the fact that he hit an ocean at that speed, he is certainly going to collide with more than a few postmen, joggers, dog walkers ... and semi trucks. Sonic may also have limited time to perform bursts of "hyper speed" and cant sustain it.

snippet.textDisplay: When you use the entire road length of the US to see how long it would take for Sonic to cover each road, your taking it to account that Sonic will take optimum paths and not travel any road more than once. Additionally you're expecting him to recognise any previous paths he's taken. It's entirely possible for him to cover the east half of the US, get close to the west coast but go back to covering the entirely of the east and not realise so the time he could take could be way longer than you calculated...
